8	/*
9	 * Flat hash consists of dynamic DATA STRUCTURE and set of OPERATIONS.
10	 *
11	 * DATA STRUCTURE
12	 *    Consists of 3 parts allocated one by one in chunk of memory:
13	 *
14	 *    HASH_CELLS   array of indices of 1st list element in ELEMENTS array,
15	 *                 or 0 if list is empty. HASH_CELLS_length is power of 2.
16	 *    DESCRIPTOR   contains hash_mask (= HASH_CELLS_Length - 1), ELEMENTS_size,
17	 *                 number of last used element in ELEMENTS,
18	 *                 number of deleted elements in ELEMENTS;
19	 *    ELEMENTS     array of: [index of next element, hash_function(KEY),
20	 *                 link to stored value or NULL if element is not used)].
21	 *
22	 * PROPERTIES of flat hash
23	 *     It is relocatable in memory, preserve insertion order, expand and shrink
24	 *     depending on number elements in it, maximum occupancy is 2^32-2 elements.
25	 *
26	 * OPERATIONS
27	 *    ADD element by key S with value V
28	 *      Prerequisite: be sure if flat hash not contains S. If ELEMENTS has free
29	 *      space after last element, then this element is populated by: V,
30	 *      hash_function(S), S. Then element is added to correspondent HASH_CELL.
31	 *      In case when no free element in ELEMENTS, DATA STRUCTURE is expanded by
32	 *      expnad_elts(). It does the following: ELEMENTS_size is increased by
33	 *      EXPAND_FACTOR, which value is expected to be > 1. For fast access to
34	 *      stored values, HASH_CELLS_size need to be big enough to provide its low
35	 *      population: in average less than 1 element per HASH_CELL.  So,
36	 *      if HASH_CELLS_size < ELEMENTS_size then it will try doubling
37	 *      HASH_CELLS_size, until new HASH_CELLS_size >= ELEMENTS_size. Now
38	 *      new HASH_CELLS_size and new ELEMENTS_size are both defined. New
39	 *      expanded hash is obtained as:
40	 *          if HASH_CELLS_size is not increased, then
41	 *              reallocate full DATA STRUCTURE,
42	 *          else
43	 *              create new DATA STRUCTURE and populate it
44	 *              by ELEMENTS from old DATA STRUCTURE.
45	 *          Replace old DATA STRUCTURE by new one and release old one.
46	 *
47	 *    FIND element by key S
48	 *      HASH_CELLS is array which contains cells of hash
49	 *      table. As entry to the table the following index is used:
50	 *          cell_num = hash_function(S) & hash_nask
51	 *      hash_function is external and it is not specified here, it is needed to
52	 *      be good hash function for Ss, and produce results in range from 0 to
53	 *      at least 2^32 - 1; hash_mask is located in DESCRIPTOR, and it is equal
54	 *      to HASH_CELLS_size - 1, where HASH_CELLS_size is always power of 2.
55	 *      hash cell contains (may be empty) list of hash elements with same
56	 *      cell_num. Now run over the list of elements and test if some element
57	 *      contains link to S. Test function is external and is not specified here.
58	 *
59	 *    DELETE element by key S
60	 *      Locate S in ELEMENTS and remove it from elements list. Update number
61	 *      of removed elements in hash_decriptor. Mark deleted
62	 *      element as not used/deleted. If number of deleted elements is big
63	 *      enough, then use shrink_elts(): it removes gaps in ELEMENTS, shrinks if
64	 *      required HASH_CELLS, and creates new DATA STRUCTURE.
65	 *
66	 *    ENUMERATE all elements in order of insertion
67	 *      Returns one by one used elements from ELEMENTS.
68	 */
